snippet.textDisplay:
I am so sad for Kobe Briant and his daughter death, but I can't help thinking about the families of the other victims. What about THEIR loss. They lost daughters too, they lost a husband / a brother / a sister...In the news I watched nobody ever said "Lets talk about the other victims for a second and lets think about their young lifes: there were at least 3 more girls on board around the same age of Gianna, probably her friends. Nobody is talking about them. It could be a request from the families but all this shock for JUST Kobe Briant's death I think it's not fair. He is the only one who will be remembered as the victim of this crash, the orhers will become collaterals, nobody will remember them, apart from their relatives....I'm sorry for the long post, but I felt it needed to be said and shared...am I too sensitive? What do you think?
P.s. I live in Switzerland so I don't have access to many US TV channels apart from CNN and a couple of others.

We say that the hour of death cannot be forecast. But when we say this, we imagine that the hour is placed in an obscure and distant future. It never occurs to us that it has any connection with the day already begun, or that Death could arrive this same afternoon - this afternoon which is so certain, and which has every hour filled in advance.
Tod's speech at the Flight 180 memorial.
Final Destination
